segments.text: in Texas.
OK, let me first of all point out, I spent one summer in Austin studying under Hugo Leipziger and getting acquainted with some of the faculty.
This was in 1947, studying under some of the faculty there who were in the School of Architecture.
Individually, there are several people
through the years that seem to have had especially strong interest in planning at UT Austin.
Hugo, of course, being one of those.
But what I have seen at that institution is planning being pushed to one side, never accepted as either an equal partner or a parallel operation
compared to the rest of the program in the School of Architecture.
That's point one.
Point two, at UT Arlington, very strong dominance by architecture faculty over planning, and I think more so than in Austin, a view being expressed by
the head of the School of Architecture, that architects know how to plan, but planners don't know how to do architecture.
Who was the head?
I don't know who it is now.
Box at one time was out there.
Do you mean Box?
Well, Box was one of those.
Of course, he's now at UT Austin.
Now at UT Austin, that's right.
But he was one of the influences.
On the other hand, I must tell you, my daughter, Molly, just recently has enrolled in some architecture courses at UT Arlington.
And one of the instructors is a person that worked for me when I had my own private practice in Fort Worth from 69 until 75.
And this person is Dick Ferrier, who's an excellent illustrator, very talented individual.

And he commented to Molly how much he appreciated working in and for a planner in that environment as distinguished from working in an architectural office, which I thought was kind of interesting because he made this connection.
I think the thing that has happened

at UT Arlington has perhaps been one more of disappointment in the lack of raising the level of sights of the academic side, failure to raise the sights of community leadership about the contributions, the potential contributions of planning
in the local communities.
Now let me just share something by contrast.
When Bill Parker, my predecessor in Austin, was still a student at UT Austin, he was out in the field doing, as an undergraduate thesis, doing a study in a community.
It was a community up here near Wichita Falls.
He engendered a lot of positive support for planning through that.
But I don't hear of that, haven't heard of that since coming out of students out of UT Austin.
I hate to say it, I haven't heard of the students coming out of A&M, but I haven't heard of the students coming out of Arlington.
I don't hear of them going out in the summer and doing the study and getting a lot of community support and very positive interest and not making the splash, but
leaving something behind that the people in the community can hang their hats on and feel good about.
The only times that I've heard anything, it seems to have been more in the nature of a very academic .
Do us a quick and dirty sketch plan.
And that's not where you build a lot of support across the state for programs like this.
My own feeling is that the programs need to be preparing those students, whether it's in terms of year structure, freshman, sophomore, junior, senior, and then two years of graduate study.
But they need to be building themselves into a position where the students get out
in an active situational context at some point, whether it's fourth year or graduate year, working on these studies.
Excuse me, just a minute.
Let me add one additional footnote to all of this in terms of my concern.
I'm speaking initially here of the concept of the planning program built into a bachelor of city planning.
I think what happened at UT Arlington was this concept of urban design taking over.
And anybody who graduated urban design, therefore, was a planner.
Ergo was a planner.
And as I commented to you a little earlier, Bob, I see people practicing architecture, people who are acknowledged

the Dallas community as being good architects whose work, when you look at it on the ground from the outside, do not reflect an understanding of the relationships of the building to the landscape to the circulation patterns for pedestrians on site to automobiles on site, even use the hotel where you were staying.
do not understand what motivates people to act as they do, like where they park.
And we have a classic example up the street here where everybody's parking along a main thoroughfare.
Rather than driving in and getting at their front door, they're coming in the back door just because it happens to be close to the thoroughfare.
Things such as that that are a recognition of lack
consideration of the sociology, the human scale, the motivational things that affect people.
Activity patterns.
Activity patterns, yes.
The whole way people live is not, outside the building is not seen as something to be considered.
It's only what's inside the building.
And you take care of these other things in a
maybe in a sophisticated appearance way, but you don't take care of them in terms of the generic operation of that little community of people.
So the double car garage is converted to a storeroom.
Right.
And we have all the cars parked out in the driveway.
All around the street.
Simply because people find that that's really where they want to be.
And nobody thought about where these people are going to park.
There's no

I guess my concern here is that negatively, because the schools of architecture don't seem to deal with the problems of out-of-building activities and what motivates human beings out of the building, they frankly do a lot of damage, particularly in site planning.
But that spills over into the larger domain of what happens
when you dump traffic on streets and where people are going for their shopping and all of the other things.
In terms of undergraduate programs, and you pointed out, you do not have an undergraduate program in city planning.
But I think that one of our failures is the lack of a good, solid foundation program that will lead students into
a two-year graduate program in planning.
And I don't see it as anything less than a two-year professional degree program.
I think it has to be that.
You mentioned that at A&M, that, in essence, is what you have in the students.
You have this field experience requirement, the internship.
I think that's essential in a graduate program.
I don't see that it can be any other way.

But if anybody is going to be telling folks, when you come out of a design school at the undergraduate level, you are prepared to be a planner, then I would want to look very closely at the design of that curriculum to find out whether they are getting some understanding of
all of these human elements that are involved.
And most design schools don't want to relinquish that time so that those human elements are going to be adequately discussed.

There's not, other than a student accidentally in an undergraduate program taking a course in psychology, one course maybe, or one or two courses in sociology, or maybe taking beyond the required state government course
of course, in local government.
Other than that, they don't get much that says, here is the in which this planning activity goes on.
It's kind of, to me, as if the message that Patrick Geddes made years and years ago from his outlook tower in Edinburgh, you have to look at the total picture.
You can't do your design in the absence of the total picture.
Now, this is what made me wonder initially when I first took a look at the planning in Anchorage and then later on the planning in Fort Worth, the sector approach.
Because I had severe questions.

professionally about the success of the sector approach and if it would indeed be compatible with a comprehensive approach okay let me respond to that because I think we did some things there that did show compatibility one was that as recommendations came in from the sector councils the sector planning councils
Who led those?
These were the staff assisted, but really the people in that sector were the ones who identified what they saw as their critical problems.
The staff responded and said, all right, here are your problems, here are your alternatives in dealing with this, and here are the consequences of alternatives.
Then the people thrashed through the process
Is this better or is this better or is this better?
And they would come back then and say, for our sector, here is what we would like to see.
That was a recommendation of the Planning Commission.
So the staff then operated more or less like a secretariat.
A technical secretariat that also was the transmission line for information and that the sector planning councils could and did repeatedly ask for technical information.
whether it was in transportation, whether it was in parks, open space, whether it was in housing, whether it was in commercial industrial, whatever, commercial generators, whatever.
So it was a constant two-way street.
But the results of that went to the planning commission.
And the commission said, this fits within the guidelines or the principles that we have adopted.
about circulation, about open space, about housing.
We want you, staff, to go back and inform the Sector Planning Council that we find these principles being satisfied, these concepts acceptable, but here's one that we can't buy.
And here's why we can't buy it.
Because the adjoining sector has a different set of constraints or problems to deal with.
Whatever it might be.
asked them to go through that and explain to them what these problems are in this other sector.
Through that process, there was a lot of sharing and there were some changes in things.
But let me tell you, the one thing that has been very successful in that program, sector one, which is the TCU area, and it was chosen purely by happenstance,
The Sector Planning Council in that sector began in 1967 or 68.
68, I guess.
Those people are still identified.
They identify themselves as members of the Sector Planning Council.
And they, either in a large group or with representatives
will appear at the city council meetings and say, we represent the sector planning council from sector one.
Here is what we recommended in the plan.
Here's what the planning commission adopted.
And here's what we expect you to live up to.
Have you found that the sector planning councils have ever been an incubation mechanism for rising politicals or people?
Oh, yes.
Yes, it did.
In fact, it was very interesting.

In the first two sectors, the city council member from that sector, who happened to live in that sector, wherever it might have been, the county commissioner who happened to live in that sector, the school board member who happened to live in that sector,
they would always show up at sector planning council meetings.
And I talked with a couple of those people, and they told me this.

They said, in essence, it came down to, we feel not an obligation to be here, but as people who are elected to represent maybe the city at large at that time or who live in this area or do represent a district here, we feel it's our obligation
to be here and to keep on top of what these people are saying.
Otherwise, we cannot represent them.
Like Martin Meyerson said, it's sort of a pulse-taking operation.
Right.
And it was more than that.
It was more than that, because they would also infuse information about what was financially possible, what the constraints were on city or county or school district.
They could do that.
And they could do it.
And they could do it authoritatively.
And the people knew these were our neighbors.
So there was a high level of acceptance.
Now, in the later sectors, I don't know how successful that involvement was or how extensive it was, but I do know it worked in the first couple sectors, very much so.
I suppose it would depend on resident leadership.
Right.
In answer to one of your questions, though, about the sectors, in sector one, which was the TCU area,

We actually, as a result of the involvement of the people, changed the boundaries of the sector because there was an area east of TCU that said, these were the people speaking in this area, we do not belong in that sector.
We belong in the south sector.
We have more that we are.
compatible with in terms of ideas and concerns and needs with people who are two miles to the east of us than with people who are two blocks to the west of us.
And so the Sector Planning Council in that case voted to recommend back to the Planning Commission that the boundaries be changed.
And so they weren't, the sector boundaries weren't precise lines.
They wound up showing this precise lines on the map, but they were conceptual lines, if you would.
They were corridors more than anything else, sort of gray zones around the sectors.
And to that extent, I think the sector planning approach has been very successful.
If nothing else, the fact that it has kept people for 15 and 20 years involved in their community, where before that they were speaking as one, they then felt they had
a group that was knowledgeable, that had gone through a lot of discussion, spent many, many hours arguing pros and cons on issues, and that they could speak with authority.
It sounds like a substantially different experience than what happened in Austin with the neighborhood planning council.
Oh, yes.
Yeah.
I don't think there's anything comparable in the Austin experience.
Well, there was.
Initially, but this large...
Yes, and largely this then was bypassed by staff, much to the chagrin of people like Joan Bartz and so forth, who was president of the neighborhood councils.
It ended up with the Austin Tomorrow Plan, which was a non-plan, and had to...
be given redirection by the governing body, the city council, because there was no plan diagram.
All it was was a word plan.

And now, of course, with the departure of Dick Lilly, the new directors, of course, they have two planning departments now, have been directed to move ahead with the formulation of a comprehensive plan for Austin.
What do you think of them apples?
So we'll just have to see what comes out of it all.

I guess one of the things I would say about Austin is that they may not have, and I don't know what the scale was on their neighborhood planning councils, but it may well have been that what we saw in Fort Worth
was multiple neighborhoods forming a sector.
I see.
Austin, in other words, I guess if you translate that into Austin, it would be all of the east side from the inter-regional highway all the way out would be a sector.
They may have split that into several units.
And when you do that, then we were talking basically
in Fort Worth of communities of a minimum of 50,000 population as a sector.
That was kind of a ballpark figure, unless it was essentially undeveloped area, in which case the 50,000 was still seen as a projected total population.
That was a minimum, 50,000, 60,000, 70,000 as the population area.
Well, that's a good-sized community.
Oh, yeah.
That's a lot different than a neighborhood.
Oh, yeah.
So that may have been part of the difference.
Coming back to the programs and planning, the other thing I would say is this.
The universities, you and I have talked about the idea, and frankly, I agree with it because of my own experience at East Texas State, the universities, I think,
need to get together on their planning programs.
I think they need to do it in a couple of ways.

One is, and I speak here primarily of the graduate programs, one is to identify a common core of courses that students might take at any one of the three schools and that would be acceptable at any one
of the three schools, speaking of UT, Austin, and A&M, and UT Arlington.
This we're trying to do in the adult continuing ed program at TWU North Texas, East Texas.
And we're going to be successful.
I have no doubt about it.
It may take a time before that can be accomplished, but I think that there is much for the three universities that have planning programs
you gain from studying the federation of North Texas area universities in terms of how the graduate programs can be federated to the mutual advantage of the universities and the students.
For example, the location of A&M is hardly what you'd call urban oriented.
Oh, no.
And we are under continuing disadvantage in not only attracting students to the campus because of that, but also in our outreach programs and our community service programs and our lab work.
And it would be far more useful if these students could be located in their second year in an urban environment.
Sure.
It wouldn't matter much where they were located in their first year.
That's right.
For the basic courses, I don't see that it makes an awful lot of difference because those are essentially internally oriented.
But the externally oriented courses, they really need to have the opportunity to see what happens on the ground.

I'm not, I guess the one thing that gives me concern there is that the planning agencies in the state, the city planning agencies, don't have, they're not the best work environment because of somewhat being fraught with some political pressures that are totally external and therefore having some real problems that way and the other is just a,
maybe not having the strength that they ought to in city government.
Those kinds of things bother me.
But there's no reason that students from the three schools could not be assigned to work in given localities in a summer internship or in a long term.
I see even the possibility if the graduate programs in planning were

coupled with a graduate program in urban studies, for example, or a graduate program in geography, or a graduate program in sociology, not social work, but sociology, that students could not be put together in teams out in the field.
One of my concerns
and it has been a longstanding concern, is that too many people who are identified as professional planners come only out of a design background and know nothing else.
Academically, they don't have any other orientation.
I've been in a very fortunate position in various places where I've worked.
I'm hiring people who are geographers, and I look for geographers to hire.
I've hired people who are sociologists, and I look for either sociology or economics as the primary background of individuals.
I've looked for people who have been engineers, not planners, but engineers who would have some understanding of the mechanisms of the community.
Frankly, so I'd have somebody to counterbalance the engineering advice coming from public works departments and places like that.
I've looked for people who really had a background in public administration.
In fact, when I was in Fort Worth, I hired a fellow who had his PhD from Indiana in public administration.
An excellent person.
I felt very good about it.
He was constantly generating ideas and helping loosen up the whole staff.
Helped me tremendously.
But I don't see the planning programs trying to get their students to hook into individuals like that.
One of my best experiences in graduate school was at Oklahoma when I was teamed up with a fellow who was doing
graduate work in architecture at OU.
And he was interested in some regional issues and the implication of some regional issues for planning and architecture.
He got assigned to my team.
Two of us were a team doing things together.
It was great.
It was absolutely great.
And I found that a very, very rewarding experience.
Jack Schultz, he was in Tulsa one time.
In fact, for many years he was in Tulsa.
Bob, let me back up for a moment.
Now that it's the next morning, I'd like to just reflect on a couple of things.
When I was in...

Austin, the person who served for several years as assistant planning director was Bob Green, Robert Green, who was very well liked by staff and had a landscape architecture background from the University of Western Mass.
And he then left and went on to work in San Antonio.
The other two individuals that I neglected to mention were people in Fort Worth.
Alvin Marsden, who came from the University of Washington as an architect, he had come in to our staff.
And he was very good in terms of stimulating some design
concepts in connection with planning efforts for Fort Worth.
The other person was Ruben D. Ramirez, who was also a product of University of Washington, who likewise did a good deal in the area of design.
Al Marsden returned to Washington during the time period before I left the city of Fort Worth.
Ruben Ramirez went to Albuquerque as head of the planning department up there and then later returned to the Dallas-Fort Worth area and is currently in practice in the Dallas area.
Those also are perhaps contacts you might want to make.
Well, a little bit further beyond the Fort Worth experience, in my own private practice, I did planning work in conjunction with.
Pardon the interruption.
In my own private practice, in conjunction with some engineering firms and other firms in landscape architecture,
did a series of planning studies in towns
